# Algorithm Complexity Budget

Pair with `karpathy-guidelines` §"Simplicity First" and the **complexity-sentinel** Stop hook (`.claude/hooks/complexity_sentinel.py`). This rule names the cost budget so reviewers and the hook agree on what counts as "too much".

## Default budget (per function)

| Metric | Soft limit | Hard limit | Action if exceeded |
|---|---:|---:|---|
| Loop nest depth | 2 | 3 | Comment the algorithmic trade-off above the loop. Extract inner body to a named helper if the work is reusable. |
| Conditional nest depth (if/elif) | 3 | 4 | Replace with early-return guards, dispatch dict, or polymorphism. |
| Function body | 40 LOC | 60 LOC | Split into named sub-functions whose names describe each step. |
| Branch count (cyclomatic-ish) | 8 | 12 | Same as conditional nest. |

Defaults match `complexity_sentinel.py`. Override per project in `.agent-toolkit/complexity_budget.json` — see `templates/agent_toolkit/`.

## Big-O annotation rule

Any function whose worst-case cost is **worse than O(n log n)** in input size MUST include a one-line comment above the definition stating:

```
# O(n²) — acceptable here because <n is bounded ≤ 50> / <one-shot migration> / <other concrete reason>.
```

No annotation = reviewer assumes O(1) or O(n) and rejects on Big-O grounds. The point is not to forbid quadratic code (sometimes correct), but to make the cost explicit and reviewable.

## Reuse over rewrite

Before adding a new pass over an existing data structure, ask:

1. Is there already a function that iterates this structure? (Use the **Reuse Probe** hook / `reuse-first-then-write` skill.)
2. Can the new work fold into that single pass?

Two sequential O(n) passes are usually preferable to a fused O(n) pass that becomes unreadable — but three or more passes over the same data is a refactor signal (collect once, transform many).

## Anti-patterns (each rejected at code review unless justified)

| Anti-pattern | Better |
|---|---|
| Nested list comprehension `[x for a in A for b in a for c in b ...]` | Extract a generator function; name each level. |
| `if cond1: if cond2: if cond3:` (3+ deep) | Guard clauses `if not cond1: return ...` |
| Function > 60 LOC doing 4+ unrelated steps | Split into 4 named functions; the outer fn becomes a 4-line orchestrator. |
| `for x in A: for y in B: if x == y: ...` (O(n·m) lookup) | Build a `set(B)` once; lookup is O(1) per x. |
| Recursive call without `@lru_cache` on overlapping subproblems | Memoize, or convert to bottom-up iteration. |

## When to override the budget

Override is fine if you state WHY in a code comment that the reviewer (and future you) can grep:

```python
# Complexity-budget: loop-nest 4 OK — matrix is fixed 4×4×4×4 (RGBA cube).
```

The complexity-sentinel hook does not block; it surfaces. The rule above tells reviewers when "warned but shipped" is acceptable.

